fields.label: Google Maps API Key Instructions
fields.message:
Step 1: Create a Google Cloud Project

  1. Go to the Google Cloud Console.
  2. Sign in with your Google account.
  3. In the top menu, click the project dropdown (a list icon) and then click New Project.
  4. Enter the project name (optional: select a billing account) and click Create.

Step 2: Enable Google Maps API

  1. After your project is created, you'll be redirected to your project’s dashboard.
  2. In the left-hand sidebar, navigate to APIs & Services > Library.
  3. In the search bar, type Google Maps, and click Enable for each APIs you need.
    • - Maps JavaScript API.
    • - Places API.
    • - Geocoding API.

Step 3: Create API Credentials (API Key)

  1. In the left sidebar, go to APIs & Services > Credentials.
  2. Click Create Credentials and select API Key.
  3. Google Cloud will generate a new API key for you.
  4. Copy this key—you’ll need it for integrating into your application.

Step 4: Restrict API Key

  1. To avoid unauthorized use of your API key, you should restrict it.
  2. While in APIs & Services > Credentials, click on your newly created API key.
  3. Under Application restrictions, select the restriction type based on how your key will be used:
  4. Select HTTP referrers (websites).
  5. Enter the address of this website.
  6. Click Save.

Step 5: Set Up Billing (Mandatory for Google Maps API)

  1. Google Maps services require an active billing account. You get a certain amount of free usage every month, but billing is required for overages.
  2. In the left sidebar, go to Billing, and link your billing account to your project. If you don’t have one, Google will guide you through setting it up.

Once done, your API key is ready for use! Copy and paste it in the field above.
